Author::::Varun Mahan
DateTime::::2016-02-25T08:32:55Z
Android is the name for the basic operating system the phone uses. It was developed by Google to be open source, meaning others can modify the system aesthetically and practically. This is similar to Linux on PCs, it also means that anyone can develop a software for those operating systems without special permission from Google (getting it on the play /app store for distribution is another matter entirely). This is in total contrast to Apples philosophy, which guards access to its basic code jealously. In pure philosophical terms that approach takes away the end users freedom, while open source allows the end user the flexibility we have come to expect from computers. This may not matter much to an end user like yourself, and isn't why people nowadays trumpet Android as superior, that's so because the user interface is quite simply easier to use and more practical. The only real analogy I can think of this morning is the improvement from a stick shift to an automatic in terms of ease of use, and intuitive features. Operating systems can be complex and so the benefits aren't immediately obvious but become apparent after prolonged use. 



